    <h1>Design System at Devex</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Reading time 4 minutes</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Project overview</h2>
    <p>Soon after joining Devex, designers saw a clear consistency issue. By working in separate squads <strong>different UIs for the same elements</strong> had been created. This struck us as a big risk for the user experience, making the site harder to understand. I proposed to start <strong>building an integrated Design System</strong> to eventually solve these inconsistencies.</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Auditing without an audit</h2>
    <p>Devex defines itself as a news media platform, but its platform includes five other products related to the global development market, each of them targeting different user personas. At the time (and even now), you could clearly find <strong>three different approaches to the design</strong> within the platform: one for news- and marketing-related content, other for the jobs- and recruitment-related content and finally the funding-related content, closer to jobs but with its own unique design patterns.</p>
    <p>In order to successfully <strong>close that gap</strong>, we needed to gain perspective of what visual and functional patterns were alike, which were close enough and which ones were unique to their area. I proposed making a <strong>UI audit</strong> of the platform to collect all those items and then analyze how they related with each other.</p>
    <figure class="img__full-width">
      <img decoding="async" width="1347" height="875" src="https://apedraza.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/news-auditing.png" alt="">
      <figcaption>UI audit collection of components found in News section pages</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>There were too many elements and we already had projects waiting for us in the pipeline. We agreed on three actions to be done when facing any UI project:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>When working over an existing page, create a component replicating existing reused elements as they are at the moment.</li>
      <li>While creating new elements, look for similar items within that same domain.</li>
      <li>If none of the above applies, discuss with the rest of the team about this addition's value and get agreement, or look for alternatives.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>After a year in the job, we had the most common components of the Devex platform scattered along different project files.</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Scaling the pre-existing UI toolkit</h2>
    <p>The front-end engineers were working with a <strong>UI toolkit based on Bootstrap 5</strong> components. Some of them were basic Bootstrap components modifying the styles to match the Devex brand, others had a wrapper around them to expand their functionality. None of them had cases of use.</p>
    <p>We started working by downloading a Bootstrap 5 UI toolkit for Figma and scaled by adapting those assets <strong>into our own Devex UI toolkit file</strong>.</p>
