  <section>
    <h2>Getting bigger</h2>
    <p>We had gathered all tokens and had at our disposition all Bootstrap assets as well as all the components resulting from our on-the-spot auditings. We were ready to get serious about <strong>building the Design System</strong>.</p>
    <p>However, on the implementation side things weren't so easy: what for the Design team was one single environment, for the Front-end team involved juggling up to three different technologies. Getting to the point of having reusable components applicable throughout the platform wasn't something feasible yet.</p>
    <p>Regardless, the Design team thought that there was still value in evolving this system within the Figma environment. We have continued to pursue a <strong>standardized and cohesive design language</strong>, working to make our components reusable and consistent, at least when it comes to design work. As a result, we have replicated most of Devex's components and patterns in Figma and defined use cases for them.</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Conclusions</h2>
    <p>Design systems are never done and this one is far from mature. While it is applied in some areas of the Devex platform, it is far from being used throughout the platform. Nevertheless, </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Around <strong>70% of the patterns</strong> of the site have already been gathered into the Design System Figma's file.</li>
      <li>We have <strong>improved UI design delivery speed</strong> by avoiding the need of creating low-fidelity mock-ups (we already have high-fidelity assets at our disposal) nor specifying interactions, when already available within the UI toolkit.</li>
      <li>We also have some <strong>responsive templates</strong> in place, allowing us to work in some projects within their UI context without the need of replicating those pages.</li>
      <li>Freeing our time of UI design gives designers the chance to put <strong>more effort into research</strong>, resulting in <strong>better UX work</strong>.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>There is still a lot to work when it comes to rule and define cases of use, as there are many projected standardizations waiting for the right project to be implemented. In anyway, the road towards a systematic UI design is already paved and it goes towards a consistent platform.</p>
  </section>
